{"product_id": "12100", "page": 123, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-04-29", "text": "The game that started it all; it has influenced a whole slew of known games, and therefore dare I say the most important game of the new millennium.\nDespite its age, it remains one of the best, most-enjoyable open-world games out there thanks to the fact that it resembles a well-made pizza pie: based with good gameplay and an ok storyline like tomato sauce with basil, topped with cheesy innuendos and characters and sprinkled with just the right amount of difficulty, like the occasional black olive.\nEven gets frustrating at times, but it is baked with such care, that it stays crisp through the end.\nWASTED", "hours": 4.5, "user_id": "76561198130008734", "username": "Snoozentus", "products": 28, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "12100", "page": 123, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-04-27", "text": "+\nWide range of resolutions (Even for laptops, I was surprised);\nVarious types of weaponry;\nWeather effects (Fog, rain, sun.);\nBig open world;\nBunch of side missions and main missions;\nSound options;\nGreat themed radio stations;\nGreat voice acting;\nGreat plot;\nLenghty game.\n-\nMute protagonist;\nNo graphical options;\nWeak physics;\nNo ingame map;\nIf you fall into the water, you're dead;\nCan't get out of the car while it moves. (If the car is on fire and you are driving it full speed you're gonna die.);\nNo auto-save.\nPlayed it at 1366 x 768 x 32 with 30 Fps cap, max allowed on my laptop.\nScore: 8/10.", "hours": 21.1, "username": "[MGSFC] R1SK", "products": 934, "early_access": false}
